WEBVTT

01:15.116 --> 01:17.702
December 1916.

01:22.123 --> 01:25.627
The Society for
         Psychical Research

01:25.668 --> 01:29.923
whose publications include
      "Phantasms of The Living"

01:29.964 --> 01:33.760
and "Human Personality and
   Its Survival Of Bodily Death"

01:35.345 --> 01:38.181
are reporting an
     extraordinary phenomenon.

01:41.476 --> 01:45.313
Mr. Charles Chaplin,
      motion picture comedian,

01:46.189 --> 01:48.691
has been cited in
        hundreds of places,

01:51.444 --> 01:52.487
simultaneously.

01:56.032 --> 01:58.535
From the Atlantic
          to the Pacific,

01:59.077 --> 02:01.871
from the Canadian
       boundary to the Gulf,

02:02.997 --> 02:06.209
people wait at stations
        to see Mr. Chaplin.

02:09.045 --> 02:10.630
In the same hour,

02:10.672 --> 02:14.425
crowds are gathering at
     hotels across the country.

02:17.095 --> 02:20.974
"Have you got the Chaplin-oia?"
        asks one newspaper.

02:21.015 --> 02:22.809
Others report the Chaplin Fever,

02:23.726 --> 02:26.146
the Chaplin Craze,

02:26.187 --> 02:27.397
Charlie-mania.

02:28.898 --> 02:31.359
"Chaplin-itis,"
         runs one headline,

02:31.401 --> 02:34.028
"Has spread across America.

02:37.991 --> 02:41.744
Bootlegs, counterfeits, and
    imitators flood the market.

02:45.665 --> 02:48.418
Lookalike contests spring
        up across the globe.

02:55.592 --> 02:58.469
It's rumored that Chaplin
   himself entered such a contest

03:00.763 --> 03:02.557
and came 20th.

03:05.018 --> 03:07.061
People demand to know,

03:08.605 --> 03:13.067
"Who is the Real
         Charlie Chaplin?"

04:27.850 --> 04:29.477
When we think of
          Charlie Chaplin,

04:31.396 --> 04:33.481
we picture this man.

04:37.110 --> 04:40.530
This is the moment he first
      steps on to the screen.

04:47.161 --> 04:48.788
And he looks at us.

04:55.753 --> 04:58.172
He reappears soon
       after in other films.

05:01.884 --> 05:02.760
Here he is again.

05:09.684 --> 05:10.768
And here.

05:16.524 --> 05:19.193
And he keeps looking at us.

05:28.077 --> 05:30.538
But this is not Charlie Chaplin.

05:33.041 --> 05:34.917
This man has no name.

05:37.795 --> 05:39.714
He has no fixed address.

05:42.633 --> 05:44.469
No family.

05:46.846 --> 05:50.058
No set point in space or time.

05:56.105 --> 05:58.066
You can't pin him down.

06:04.864 --> 06:08.868
The only constants
       are the hat, the cane,

06:08.910 --> 06:10.828
the boots and the mustache.

06:12.872 --> 06:15.083
Sometimes just the mustache.

06:21.798 --> 06:23.383
So who is he?

06:28.137 --> 06:30.598
He's been called the little man.

06:32.809 --> 06:34.811
The little fellow.

06:36.312 --> 06:37.146
The Tramp.

06:40.149 --> 06:44.445
He's a character played
        by Charlie Chaplin.

06:58.793 --> 07:02.505
"The Tramp" will make
        Chaplin more famous

07:02.547 --> 07:06.134
than any king,
         queen, or emperor.

07:12.265 --> 07:16.060
More famous than any
        philosopher, artist,

07:16.102 --> 07:17.520
or religious figure.

07:22.191 --> 07:26.195
Famous in a way that
      no one has been before.

07:42.128 --> 07:47.300
Chaplin makes "The Tramp" and
    "The Tramp" makes Chaplin.

07:49.844 --> 07:55.016
You can't see one without
       looking at the other.

07:58.811 --> 08:00.354
They tell each other's stories.

08:03.941 --> 08:05.026
So where do we start?

08:10.990 --> 08:12.867
Here's how Chaplin starts.

08:24.212 --> 08:28.216
1889 begins with a total
         eclipse of the sun.

08:31.677 --> 08:34.722
This year, the Eiffel
     tower opens to the public.

08:36.766 --> 08:38.392
Adolph Hitler is born.

08:40.561 --> 08:43.064
In Kyoto, Nintendo is founded.

08:45.691 --> 08:46.901
They make playing cards.

08:49.570 --> 08:52.240
Electric streetlights are
     being installed in London

08:53.324 --> 08:55.701
where Jack the Ripper
         remains at large.

08:58.204 --> 09:00.248
The pizza margarita is invented.

09:02.708 --> 09:05.545
They're still working
         on the aero plane.

09:11.801 --> 09:13.928
This is how movies look in 1889.

09:18.516 --> 09:22.144
89.

09:22.436 --> 09:25.106
These are
   recordings of the human voice.

09:30.820 --> 09:32.905
Of birdsong.

09:36.784 --> 09:38.244
Of music.

10:02.268 --> 10:04.979
Film grows up alongside Chaplin.

10:10.192 --> 10:13.529
It captures the London
     streets he roams as a kid.

10:28.628 --> 10:30.004
The children he plays with.

10:39.055 --> 10:41.557
This is the
       voice of Effie Wisdom.

10:56.072 --> 11:00.242
Captured on tape
     when she was 92 years old.

14:53.767 --> 14:56.729
It takes 12
     days for the Karno Company

14:56.770 --> 14:58.272
to cross the Atlantic.

15:04.612 --> 15:07.698
12 days in a rat
       -infested cattle boat.

15:20.336 --> 15:22.630
At first sight of land,

15:23.756 --> 15:25.966
one young man leans
         over the railing

15:28.010 --> 15:29.011
and screams out.

15:52.826 --> 15:55.120
They embark on a grueling
      tour of the continent.

15:59.333 --> 16:01.710
Playing three shows a day.

16:08.676 --> 16:11.136
Fred Karno's brand
        of knockabout comedy

16:11.178 --> 16:12.930
is intensely physical.

16:16.350 --> 16:18.102
He teaches his
        comics how to trip.

16:21.021 --> 16:24.525
How to tumble, slide and fall.

16:24.566 --> 16:26.610
How to take a punch.

16:26.652 --> 16:29.196
How to fall down a
         flight of stairs.

16:31.740 --> 16:33.993
They're the best
          in the business.

16:35.744 --> 16:39.957
And wherever they go,
     one performer stands out.

16:50.759 --> 16:53.387
But his tour mates
        can't work him out.

16:56.140 --> 17:00.352
Offstage, he's quiet,
        moody and reclusive.

17:03.147 --> 17:05.274
He's usually shabby
          in appearance.

17:07.276 --> 17:10.279
Then, without warning,
        he'll dress to kill.

17:14.950 --> 17:19.455
He teaches himself the
    cello, ancient Greek, yoga.

17:22.249 --> 17:27.254
But above all he vows that
      he will not return poor.

17:38.724 --> 17:43.020
In California, a
      fortune teller tells him

17:43.062 --> 17:46.648
he will soon enter a new field

17:46.690 --> 17:49.568
in which he will earn
       a tremendous fortune.

17:55.783 --> 17:59.369
They say that fortunes are
    there to be made in America.

18:03.332 --> 18:06.668
The oil boom has created
       millionaires overnight.

18:09.046 --> 18:12.132
Henry Ford has devised
     the modern assembly line.

18:15.344 --> 18:18.806
And Nickelodeon's opening in
     cities across the country,

18:21.308 --> 18:25.395
showing motion picture
     comedies around the clock.

18:32.194 --> 18:34.488
But Chaplin isn't
      impressed by the movies.

18:36.115 --> 18:38.033
He thinks they're a passing fad.

18:44.039 --> 18:47.000
Mr. Chaplin got
    into motion pictures purely,

18:47.042 --> 18:48.794
in my mind, by accident.

18:50.254 --> 18:52.923
This is the
       voice of Mack Sennett,

18:52.965 --> 18:54.967
pioneer of movie comedy,

18:56.760 --> 18:59.054
founder of Keystone Studios,

19:01.431 --> 19:05.310
specialists in custard pie
   warfare and high-speed chases,

19:06.812 --> 19:11.859
the Mack Sennett Bathing
     Girls, the Keystone Kops.

19:14.653 --> 19:17.072
I have a comedian
    working for me at the time.

19:17.114 --> 19:18.157
His name was Ford Sterling.

19:18.198 --> 19:20.367
He was a chief of
         the Keystone Kops.

19:22.536 --> 19:24.997
One day
           Sterling quits.

19:26.665 --> 19:28.375
I said, "Oh, shucks".

19:28.417 --> 19:31.128
Suddenly
     Sennett needs a new lead.

19:32.754 --> 19:34.006
Right away, I
       thought of a comedian

19:34.047 --> 19:35.883
that I'd seen in an
        English act called,

19:35.924 --> 19:38.260
"A Night in the
        London Music Hall."

19:38.302 --> 19:40.429
I couldn't remember
       the name at the time,

19:40.470 --> 19:44.057
but I wired to New York to
    associates to find this man.

19:44.099 --> 19:47.060
And I said, his name is
 Champion, Chaprin, or Chambers,

19:47.102 --> 19:48.645
or something like that.

19:48.687 --> 19:50.022
So they traced him in

19:50.063 --> 19:52.649
and they found him in a
    small town in Pennsylvania.

19:55.110 --> 19:57.738
Sennett
      offers him $150 a week,

19:59.031 --> 20:01.033
three times the money
         he's getting now.

20:03.827 --> 20:07.664
He decides he'll stick
         it out for a year.

20:09.708 --> 20:12.211
And if Ford Sterling
       had continued with me,

20:12.252 --> 20:15.672
the chances are that Chaplin
   would have returned to England

20:15.714 --> 20:18.050
and we'd have probably
    missed the greatest comedian

20:18.091 --> 20:19.843
we've ever seen.

20:47.996 --> 20:49.790
This is
     Chaplin telling the story

20:49.831 --> 20:53.126
in a 1966 interview
        for "Life Magazine."

21:00.801 --> 21:03.095
It's one of the
   only times Chaplin has allowed

21:03.136 --> 21:05.681
a tape recorder
        within these walls.

21:20.570 --> 21:23.365
The million
          dollar question.

21:23.407 --> 21:26.034
He's been asked this countless
       times by journalists.

21:33.041 --> 21:35.460
And also by lawyers.

21:42.551 --> 21:44.219
This man looks familiar.

21:45.721 --> 21:48.098
The hat, the mustache.

21:49.975 --> 21:52.269
But this is not Charlie Chaplin.

21:56.064 --> 21:59.359
In the 1920s, this
       man releases a series

21:59.401 --> 22:04.364
of knockoff Chaplin films
   under the name Charles Aplin.

22:07.242 --> 22:12.205
Chaplin sues Aplin
        and the trial delves

22:12.414 --> 22:14.750
into the origins of the Tramp.

22:17.586 --> 22:21.423
Firstly, Aplin claims he
     wasn't imitating Chaplin.

22:22.966 --> 22:25.135
He was imitating Billy West,

22:26.595 --> 22:28.472
the famous Chaplin impersonator.

22:30.265 --> 22:33.143
"Aplin's Chaplin isn't
        Chaplin," says Aplin.

22:34.770 --> 22:39.274
Aplin's Chaplin is an imitation
    of an imitation of Chaplin.

22:42.027 --> 22:46.365
"Besides, if anyone should
    be on trial for imitation,"

22:46.406 --> 22:49.701
says Aplin, "It's Chaplin."

22:51.787 --> 22:53.830
Two of Chaplin's
         Karno colleagues,

22:53.872 --> 22:56.041
Fred Kitchen and Billy Ritchie,

22:56.083 --> 22:59.628
both claim that Chaplin's Tramp
     is an imitation of theirs.

23:01.421 --> 23:03.673
"I was the first says," Ritchie,

23:05.258 --> 23:06.843
who goes on to make a living

23:07.719 --> 23:10.389
producing knockoff
           Chaplin films.

23:13.600 --> 23:17.521
But Aplin and Chaplin, Ritchie
   and Kitchen are all following

23:17.562 --> 23:20.440
in the wake of a great
      wave of tramp comedians

23:23.318 --> 23:24.820
who have been touring
       the vaudeville circuit

23:24.861 --> 23:27.280
since the late 19th century.

23:30.117 --> 23:33.412
These comedians are
        themselves inspired

23:33.453 --> 23:34.663
by real tramps.

23:36.790 --> 23:39.459
The drifters who crisscross
     America in search of work.

23:43.296 --> 23:46.550
The homeless Chaplin grew up
   with on the streets of London.

23:49.761 --> 23:52.264
These men are more
      likely to see the inside

23:52.305 --> 23:55.267
of a police cell
        than a movie studio.

24:03.024 --> 24:05.444
But in Chapman's
        telling the creation

24:05.485 --> 24:08.321
of his Tramp is spontaneous.

24:16.371 --> 24:18.665
He's just
       made his screen debut,

24:20.292 --> 24:23.086
a clear knockoff of his
     predecessor Ford Sterling.

24:26.131 --> 24:28.216
And the reviews aren't good.

25:07.756 --> 25:10.800
In fact, the
      shoes were Sterling's,

25:10.842 --> 25:13.136
the trousers, Fatty Arbuckle's

25:13.178 --> 25:16.139
and the hat belonged
       to somebody's father.

25:18.266 --> 25:20.060
The costume isn't stolen,

25:21.269 --> 25:24.314
but it's assembled, magpie-like,

25:24.356 --> 25:26.149
from bits of other costumes.

25:50.924 --> 25:55.470
And so, we're
     back here, February, 1914.

25:56.638 --> 25:59.432
The moment he first
       steps onto the screen

26:01.643 --> 26:02.602
and looks at us.

26:16.116 --> 26:19.953
And this time the
      reviews aren't half bad.

29:01.114 --> 29:03.116
And it's
        not just New York.

29:30.351 --> 29:35.732
Why is Chaplin fever
    spreading across the world?

29:35.774 --> 29:38.985
What is it about
         this little Tramp?

29:48.244 --> 29:49.996
Well, he's funny.

29:53.708 --> 29:55.001
He can take any situation

29:57.962 --> 29:59.589
and make it silly.

30:46.052 --> 30:48.972
But it's more than that.

30:49.013 --> 30:51.975
In a society sharply
         defined by class,

30:53.518 --> 30:55.979
the Tramp not only
       stands up to the man.

30:58.523 --> 31:01.568
He gives them a kick up
     the arse for good measure.

31:11.327 --> 31:14.205
To the millions of migrants,
      dreaming of a new life,

31:17.166 --> 31:19.335
the Tramp is someone
         without a nation.

31:25.842 --> 31:27.677
Someone who has no language,

31:30.805 --> 31:32.473
but who speaks to everyone.

31:38.021 --> 31:42.150
And in a world divided
         by bitter conflict,

31:44.152 --> 31:45.904
the Tramp can make you laugh,

31:45.945 --> 31:47.614
whichever side you're on.

31:55.330 --> 31:59.292
The Tramp defies the
      boundaries of identity.

32:01.920 --> 32:04.464
He blurs gender and sexuality.

32:09.135 --> 32:11.721
He upends authority and class.

32:25.485 --> 32:26.569
He's a nobody

32:29.364 --> 32:32.158
and he belongs to everybody.

32:52.011 --> 32:53.179
In the work house

32:54.222 --> 32:56.432
Chaplin dreamed
         of becoming rich,

32:57.684 --> 33:00.395
famous and beloved.

33:06.067 --> 33:10.279
He's now the highest
      paid actor in the world.

33:13.658 --> 33:15.952
The most famous man alive.

33:23.042 --> 33:27.588
So all the
    adulation, it's not for me.

33:28.798 --> 33:30.049
It's for the little man.

33:41.853 --> 33:44.689
First impression was the eyes.

33:46.858 --> 33:50.361
They could be so warm and so
    cold in a flash of a second.

33:55.283 --> 33:57.076
Because he was a
         charmer, you know.

34:02.248 --> 34:05.084
Charlie
     was a great exhibitionist.

34:10.548 --> 34:11.591
Very flamboyant.

34:12.967 --> 34:14.343
He put on a great show.

34:22.310 --> 34:24.687
He loved to talk on any subject,

34:26.647 --> 34:29.442
pretend that he was a rebel
     and a radical politically.

34:39.285 --> 34:41.454
And he had the means
       of making people think

34:41.496 --> 34:43.748
that he was a very
          profound reader,

34:45.917 --> 34:47.710
when actually I think
       he read the first page

34:47.752 --> 34:48.961
of a number of books

34:49.003 --> 34:50.797
and made people think
      he read the whole thing.

34:56.677 --> 34:58.638
Charlie
         was always acting.

35:05.144 --> 35:08.815
Always on show, always
          the entertainer.

35:11.484 --> 35:14.487
He didn't want people to
       know the real Charlie.

35:18.116 --> 35:21.869
One's bound to be insecure
     with a childhood like his.

35:26.999 --> 35:29.043
He never felt
         anybody loved him.

35:35.550 --> 35:36.676
He never believed it.

35:41.722 --> 35:43.850
He said, "Why would
         anybody love me?"

35:58.865 --> 36:00.283
I am no psychiatrist,

36:00.324 --> 36:04.328
but it's easy to see that
    still has a fear of poverty.

36:08.833 --> 36:10.543
Don't care how
         much money he has.

36:12.336 --> 36:13.796
He still has fear of poverty.

36:59.592 --> 37:01.677
Within a few years,

37:01.719 --> 37:03.888
Chaplin has built
          his own studio,

37:06.390 --> 37:08.267
founded a distribution company,

37:11.103 --> 37:14.273
liberated himself from
 dependence on financial backers.

37:23.908 --> 37:25.326
He follows no schedule.

37:26.994 --> 37:28.621
He doesn't even follow a script.

37:31.999 --> 37:34.293
He starts with a vague idea

37:35.294 --> 37:39.298
and replays it again
        and again and again,

37:40.383 --> 37:41.550
until it becomes funny.

38:12.999 --> 38:16.711
The actors are instructed
      to perform each gesture

38:16.752 --> 38:18.629
exactly as he does

38:20.089 --> 38:22.550
as though they are mere
      extensions of his body.

38:25.386 --> 38:30.266
Every nuance, every
      glance, he makes first.

38:33.019 --> 38:35.855
His assistant says that if
    he could have done every job

38:35.896 --> 38:38.441
on set himself, he would have.

38:39.483 --> 38:43.029
As it is, he writes,
         directs, produces,

38:43.070 --> 38:46.699
edits, scores, and stars.

38:48.743 --> 38:51.495
He even tries his hand
         at hair and makeup.

38:57.960 --> 39:01.047
Finally, when he
         has total control,

39:02.340 --> 39:05.384
he begins his most
       ambitious project yet.

39:28.324 --> 39:31.744
It's the story of
        an abandoned child.

39:34.413 --> 39:39.335
Of a single mother too
        poor to care for him.

40:14.203 --> 40:17.415
In another life, the boy is
     headed for the workhouse.

40:22.795 --> 40:25.589
But in this version, when
      the authorities arrive

40:25.631 --> 40:26.674
to take him away,

40:28.801 --> 40:31.971
he's not going without a fight.

42:43.644 --> 42:46.230
It's been eight years
       since he left London.

42:49.066 --> 42:50.985
And when he finally gets back,

42:53.153 --> 42:55.281
he hears a familiar voice.

43:54.256 --> 43:58.510
He finds himself
       back in the attic room

43:58.552 --> 44:00.721
of No. 3 Pownall Terrace.

44:05.184 --> 44:08.062
Four walls that the
    Chaplin family called home.

44:11.815 --> 44:13.984
Where Chaplin's mother, Hannah,

44:14.026 --> 44:16.904
delighted him with her
     costumes and impressions.

44:20.366 --> 44:24.870
Where she struggled to make
     ends meet after her voice

44:24.912 --> 44:27.790
and then her stage
           career failed.

44:33.545 --> 44:34.838
She sat at this window

44:35.923 --> 44:38.425
and told Charlie she
      could see ghosts outside

44:41.470 --> 44:43.597
before she was dragged
         off to the asylum.

44:52.856 --> 44:56.985
And Charlie's mother
        hasn't left London.

44:59.029 --> 45:00.739
She's living in a nursing home.

45:05.619 --> 45:07.788
So when Chaplin
        returns to America,

45:12.543 --> 45:13.752
he brings her with him.

45:20.968 --> 45:23.595
But she teeters between worlds.

45:30.394 --> 45:32.813
Present and past seem to blur.

45:36.233 --> 45:39.236
When she sees her son
   dressed as a tramp, she says,

45:40.738 --> 45:45.784
"Charlie, I have to
        get you a new suit.

45:56.044 --> 45:59.923
Meanwhile, her son is
      making a Hollywood epic.

46:12.936 --> 46:17.775
One that takes the Tramp
     to the ends of the earth.

46:25.783 --> 46:30.662
But it's themes
        are closer to home.

47:53.036 --> 47:54.913
This is a test

47:55.831 --> 47:59.626
to see how my voice
        records on the film.

48:02.713 --> 48:06.133
You are now listening to
     a talking, moving picture.

48:06.174 --> 48:09.136
We believe an entirely
      new art will be created.

48:09.177 --> 48:12.431
The beginning of a new
      era in motion pictures.

48:21.148 --> 48:25.110
Suddenly the Tramp's strength

48:26.820 --> 48:28.447
becomes his weakness.

48:32.993 --> 48:34.036
He can't talk.

48:36.663 --> 48:38.415
What language would he speak?

48:40.459 --> 48:41.585
What dialect?

48:47.716 --> 48:50.886
1928 Warner axes all
        its silent projects.

48:51.970 --> 48:54.932
1929 Fox follows.

48:54.973 --> 48:56.099
By 1930,

48:58.143 --> 49:00.646
all the major
        studios are talking.

49:02.856 --> 49:07.069
One by one Chaplin's
   contemporaries start to talk.

49:07.110 --> 49:09.279
First, Laurel and Hardy.

49:09.321 --> 49:10.489
My trunk is packed

49:10.530 --> 49:13.992
and I am leaving for
      South America, tonight.

49:14.034 --> 49:15.619
Then Harold Lloyd.

49:16.703 --> 49:18.747
I don't know what to say.

49:18.789 --> 49:20.749
Well, that's nothing new, dear.

49:20.791 --> 49:22.834
Then, Buster Keaton.

49:22.876 --> 49:25.420
Well, I got a lot of
       serious talking to do

49:25.462 --> 49:27.506
and you got a lot of
      serious listening to do.

49:28.465 --> 49:31.176
The talky
        revolution is here.

49:31.218 --> 49:33.679
It's alive! It's alive!

49:33.929 --> 49:35.597
The
       public is going crazy

49:35.639 --> 49:37.849
for anything that talks.

49:37.891 --> 49:39.601
Wait a minute! Wait a minute!

49:39.643 --> 49:41.019
You ain't heard nothin'.

49:41.061 --> 49:44.022
But Chaplin
   decides to do the unthinkable.

49:45.649 --> 49:47.526
He'll make a silent film.

50:06.253 --> 50:09.131
Like most romantic comedies,

50:09.172 --> 50:12.050
"City Lights"
    turns on a misunderstanding.

50:15.512 --> 50:19.391
A blind flower girl mistakes
    the Tramp for a millionaire.

50:22.936 --> 50:27.190
Simple enough on paper,
      but there is no paper.

50:28.817 --> 50:31.069
Chaplin works without a script.

50:32.362 --> 50:35.157
And this scene is
          to drive Chaplin

50:35.198 --> 50:37.743
and everyone around him

50:38.577 --> 50:40.746
to the edge of madness.

50:43.457 --> 50:44.499
Can you tell us

50:44.541 --> 50:46.084
about the shooting
         of that sequence?

50:48.253 --> 50:49.296
Oh dear.

50:53.759 --> 50:57.262
He'd take it over and over
           and over again.

50:58.388 --> 51:00.432
I often thought
     that if he couldn't think

51:00.474 --> 51:01.767
what he was going to do next,

51:01.808 --> 51:04.561
he simply went on doing
      the same shot over again

51:04.603 --> 51:05.771
until he thought of it.

51:09.775 --> 51:10.942
Chaplain agonizes

51:10.984 --> 51:12.986
over this mistaken
           identity scene.

51:15.363 --> 51:17.115
It's the heart of the film.

51:17.157 --> 51:18.575
It has to feel right.

51:19.951 --> 51:22.120
He was
          a perfectionist.

51:22.162 --> 51:25.791
And to us it often seem
      to be exactly the same.

51:27.501 --> 51:30.003
When he'd finally
         say "It's a take,"

51:30.045 --> 51:31.463
we'd breathe a sigh of relief.

51:31.505 --> 51:34.174
And then he'd say, "Well,
    perhaps just one more time."

51:50.357 --> 51:54.236
It's not
   working. Why isn't it working?

51:58.198 --> 52:01.493
What if the rich man
        buys a flower first?

52:01.535 --> 52:04.162
Then, no.

52:06.790 --> 52:08.250
Maybe it's Virginia Cherrill.

52:30.730 --> 52:33.108
270 days
          into the shoot.

52:34.025 --> 52:35.527
Charlie fired me.

52:36.736 --> 52:39.322
It's
     Cherrill. She's not right.

52:39.364 --> 52:41.700
He needs a new
       flower girl and fast.

52:43.660 --> 52:46.371
The whole thing is going to
     cost a fortune to reshoot.

52:49.249 --> 52:51.042
He hires Georgia Hale,

52:51.084 --> 52:53.044
his leading lady
       from "The Gold Rush."

52:55.338 --> 52:57.215
He said,
       "I'm going to redo all

52:57.257 --> 52:58.758
of 'City Lights' with you."

53:01.428 --> 53:03.763
I'm gonna redo
     the whole thing with you.

53:05.348 --> 53:08.143
But, no.
      Hale's not right either.

53:10.103 --> 53:11.646
He tests other actresses.

53:16.443 --> 53:20.405
They're just not, maybe
       Cherrill was the one.

53:21.531 --> 53:23.909
He begs Cherrill to come back.

53:29.956 --> 53:32.417
It's 534 days into the shoot,

53:34.127 --> 53:36.338
but they still haven't
        got the flower scene.

53:40.133 --> 53:42.427
He shot an entire film
         around the fulcrum

53:42.469 --> 53:43.929
of this mistaken identity

53:46.223 --> 53:47.933
and it just isn't working.

53:51.353 --> 53:52.437
Then it comes to him.

53:57.400 --> 53:58.652
A slamming door.

54:01.154 --> 54:04.491
The key to Chaplin's
       defiantly silent opus

54:06.785 --> 54:07.661
is a sound.

58:03.146 --> 58:07.650
At the premiere,
      50,000 people turn out,

58:07.692 --> 58:09.861
hoping to see the Tramp
       and the flower girl.

58:13.490 --> 58:15.241
And some speculate the romance

58:15.283 --> 58:17.202
may not be confined
          to the screen.

58:20.330 --> 58:22.707
Many people
   thought I was his girlfriend,

58:22.749 --> 58:23.666
but I wasn't.

58:25.710 --> 58:30.048
I was much too old.
        I was 20. 

58:34.427 --> 58:36.054
All four
        of Chaplin's wives

58:36.095 --> 58:37.639
were young actresses.

58:39.891 --> 58:41.726
Three were teenagers.

58:45.522 --> 58:47.899
I've asked the author
     of this book to visit us.

58:47.941 --> 58:49.692
Her name is Lita Grey Chaplin.

58:49.734 --> 58:51.402
The title is "My
        life With Chaplin."

58:51.444 --> 58:54.155
We only have one
    of Chaplin's wives on tape.

58:54.197 --> 58:56.699
Second wife
      of Charlie Chaplin and-

58:56.741 --> 59:00.954
1966 she
   releases her tell-all memoir.

59:00.995 --> 59:03.540
It is a controversial
         sensational book.

59:03.581 --> 59:05.833
And here is Lita Grey Chaplin.

59:12.799 --> 59:13.967
I'm curious, Lita,

59:14.008 --> 59:16.386
to find out why
     you would write this book.

59:18.012 --> 59:19.764
I had a compulsion to write it.

59:19.806 --> 59:22.183
I felt that the story
        just had to be told

59:22.225 --> 59:24.352
or rather I had
         to tell the story.

59:24.394 --> 59:27.230
I had lived so many years
      with the untrue story.

59:27.272 --> 59:30.233
You starred in one of his movies

59:30.275 --> 59:31.901
or you appeared in
         one of his movies.

59:31.943 --> 59:33.903
"The Kid" when
        I was 12 years old.

59:47.709 --> 59:49.252
Can I ask how old you
     were when you married him

59:49.294 --> 59:50.086
or is that a secret?

59:50.128 --> 59:50.962
Sixteen.

59:52.171 --> 59:54.966
And were you then heading
    for a motion picture career?

59:56.718 --> 59:59.137
Yes, I had begun in
        "The Gold Rush," but

1:00:02.307 --> 1:00:05.810
I
    couldn't finish the picture.

1:00:05.852 --> 1:00:07.854
Charlie takes two years to
      make a picture, you know,

1:00:07.895 --> 1:00:10.940
and we became involved in
     the meantime in such a way

1:00:10.982 --> 1:00:13.192
that I couldn't have
       completed the picture.

1:00:15.445 --> 1:00:19.490
A teenage girl
   pregnant with Chaplin's child.

1:00:21.409 --> 1:00:23.286
His first wife, Mildred Harris,

1:00:24.621 --> 1:00:26.164
went through something similar.

1:00:28.082 --> 1:00:31.836
She divorced Chaplin,
       citing mental cruelty.

1:00:34.005 --> 1:00:36.507
And things don't start
        any better for Lita.

1:00:38.801 --> 1:00:40.303
We were married in Mexico

1:00:40.345 --> 1:00:43.848
because Charlie didn't want
   much said about the marriage.

1:00:43.890 --> 1:00:45.600
He was pretty bitter
         in the beginning.

1:00:45.642 --> 1:00:49.020
On the way back on the
     train, he was quite nasty.

1:00:49.062 --> 1:00:51.856
We were standing out on the
     platform between the cars

1:00:51.898 --> 1:00:53.441
while the train was traveling.

1:00:53.941 --> 1:00:56.444
And he said, we could just
      end this whole situation

1:00:56.486 --> 1:00:57.695
if you'd just jump.

1:01:05.745 --> 1:01:08.873
Two years
    later, Lita sues for divorce

1:01:11.918 --> 1:01:14.212
and full custody of
        their two children.

1:01:17.131 --> 1:01:19.217
It is, up to this point,

1:01:19.258 --> 1:01:22.345
the most expensive divorce
      in Hollywood's history.

1:01:26.057 --> 1:01:28.559
The petition is so sensational

1:01:28.601 --> 1:01:31.312
that copies of it start
      selling on the street.

1:01:37.819 --> 1:01:41.114
Lita describes him
       as a serial adulterer

1:01:41.155 --> 1:01:43.741
who cheats openly
         and compulsively.

1:01:45.493 --> 1:01:47.912
She claims he's
       paranoid and jealous.

1:01:50.206 --> 1:01:51.958
That he flies into rages,

1:01:52.959 --> 1:01:56.921
bugs her room,
        pulls a gun on her.

1:01:58.464 --> 1:02:00.091
She says he tried
          to pressure her

1:02:00.133 --> 1:02:02.135
into getting a
        backstreet abortion.

1:02:05.638 --> 1:02:10.184
Chaplin calls Lita a
    blackmailer, a gold digger,

1:02:10.226 --> 1:02:11.269
a little whore.

1:02:15.773 --> 1:02:18.860
The papers label her
       Chaplin's child bride,

1:02:18.901 --> 1:02:20.778
his school girl wife.

1:02:23.489 --> 1:02:25.992
And in a letter of support
      for the genius Chaplin,

1:02:27.785 --> 1:02:29.954
30 European
      intellectuals brand her

1:02:29.996 --> 1:02:33.624
an idiot woman, cow,

1:02:33.666 --> 1:02:36.252
slut, vermin, parasite.

1:02:44.927 --> 1:02:48.181
A part of the public
      thought that I was wrong

1:02:48.222 --> 1:02:50.057
in my divorce case.

1:02:50.099 --> 1:02:55.146
That he was the poor little
 mistreated, pathetic little man

1:02:55.354 --> 1:02:57.231
with so much pathos and all.

1:02:57.273 --> 1:02:59.942
That me and my family
         were gold diggers

1:02:59.984 --> 1:03:02.278
and all this kind of talk.

1:03:02.320 --> 1:03:05.281
And that was, that
          made me feel bad

1:03:05.323 --> 1:03:07.408
because I knew that a
       portion of the public

1:03:07.450 --> 1:03:10.203
believed a lot because
       they idolized Charlie.

1:03:15.041 --> 1:03:16.834
For many
         years afterwards,

1:03:16.876 --> 1:03:19.504
Lita struggles with
      depression and alcohol.

1:03:25.885 --> 1:03:28.387
She tries to set the story
      straight in interviews,

1:03:31.390 --> 1:03:33.184
but the topic
       frequently strays back

1:03:33.226 --> 1:03:35.019
to the matter of
         Chaplin's genius.

1:03:43.986 --> 1:03:45.196
Even after her death,

1:03:46.823 --> 1:03:49.659
biographies of Chaplin
    continue to characterize her

1:03:49.700 --> 1:03:52.703
as a manipulative and
      seductive teenage girl.

1:03:56.958 --> 1:03:59.210
Chaplin, in his autobiography,

1:04:00.127 --> 1:04:02.922
dedicates just three
         sentences to Lita.

1:04:05.383 --> 1:04:07.093
He never mentions her by name.

1:04:42.420 --> 1:04:44.630
Lita's
      story is a shocking one.

1:04:47.091 --> 1:04:51.554
But for Chaplin it
          changes nothing.

1:05:29.675 --> 1:05:31.886
Plenty has changed though.

1:05:35.348 --> 1:05:40.269
The optimism of the Roaring
 Twenties has come crashing down

1:05:41.771 --> 1:05:44.148
and at every stop
      on Chaplin's world tour,

1:05:45.900 --> 1:05:48.486
he sees the ravages of
        the Great Depression.

1:05:50.905 --> 1:05:53.950
Communists and fascists are
     fighting in the streets.

1:06:01.123 --> 1:06:04.835
Queues outside screenings
         of "City Lights,"

1:06:04.877 --> 1:06:06.504
are mistaken for bread lines.

1:06:17.640 --> 1:06:20.685
In London with Mahatma Gandhi,

1:06:20.726 --> 1:06:24.313
he discusses
       poverty, exploitation

1:06:24.355 --> 1:06:26.357
and the misuse of the machine.

1:06:29.527 --> 1:06:32.405
A film is taking shape
         in Chaplin's head.

1:07:48.981 --> 1:07:52.359
It's number one
     at the British Box Office,

1:07:52.401 --> 1:07:54.612
a smash in The States.

1:07:54.653 --> 1:07:56.447
Acclaimed in the Soviet Union.

1:07:59.075 --> 1:08:03.829
But in one country,
    the film is banned outright.

1:08:14.590 --> 1:08:16.675
Munich, 15 years earlier.

1:08:22.556 --> 1:08:25.267
A little man marches
          down the street,

1:08:25.810 --> 1:08:28.521
swishing at the air
      with some sort of cane.

1:08:31.857 --> 1:08:34.193
His comical appearance
         attracts attention,

1:08:34.819 --> 1:08:38.656
particularly his conspicuous
        toothbrush mustache.

1:08:40.991 --> 1:08:42.159
He looks very familiar.

1:08:44.995 --> 1:08:47.915
"Who is this funny little
      fellow?" someone asks.

1:08:51.627 --> 1:08:54.004
He's the leader of some
      fringe political group.

1:08:59.844 --> 1:09:02.763
"Just think," remarks
     Chaplin a few years later,

1:09:03.848 --> 1:09:06.308
"He's the madman,
          I'm the comic."

1:09:07.518 --> 1:09:09.520
But it could have been
        the other way around.

1:09:16.443 --> 1:09:20.364
Chaplin and Hitler are born
 within four days of each other.

1:09:22.908 --> 1:09:25.953
They both grow up
       adoring their mothers

1:09:25.995 --> 1:09:28.205
and resenting their
         drunken fathers.

1:09:30.541 --> 1:09:32.042
Both have known poverty.

1:09:33.169 --> 1:09:34.753
One plays a tramp on screen

1:09:36.463 --> 1:09:39.258
while the other is homeless
     on the streets of Vienna.

1:09:43.262 --> 1:09:47.057
Both are driven by a passionate
      intensity and ambition,

1:09:47.850 --> 1:09:49.393
laced with self-pity.

1:09:54.356 --> 1:09:59.486
Sound threatens Chaplin's art,
    but is the making of Hitler.

1:10:03.365 --> 1:10:05.743
They are
     both mesmeric performers.

1:10:07.870 --> 1:10:09.496
They know how to command a crowd

1:10:09.538 --> 1:10:11.665
through exaggerated gestures

1:10:11.707 --> 1:10:13.751
and heightened
         emotional appeals.

1:10:15.753 --> 1:10:19.757
Both elicit intense,
     almost physical reactions

1:10:19.798 --> 1:10:20.925
from their audiences.

1:10:22.301 --> 1:10:23.636
Chaplin makes them laugh.

1:10:25.012 --> 1:10:27.598
Hitler drives them
           into a frenzy.

1:10:33.020 --> 1:10:36.857
And then of course
       there's the mustache.

1:10:40.611 --> 1:10:42.988
But when Chaplin and
     Hitler look at each other,

1:10:44.323 --> 1:10:45.407
what do they see?

1:10:47.326 --> 1:10:48.953
The Nazis hate Chaplin.

1:10:49.828 --> 1:10:51.038
They label him a Jew

1:10:51.622 --> 1:10:54.625
and use him in their
      antisemitic propaganda.

1:11:11.976 --> 1:11:15.479
Neither can escape
    comparisons with the other.

1:11:17.147 --> 1:11:20.484
And so, as Hitler
    celebrates his 50th birthday

1:11:20.526 --> 1:11:22.778
with a military
       parade through Berlin,

1:11:24.905 --> 1:11:29.034
Chaplin is working on a
    script for his latest film.

1:11:31.245 --> 1:11:35.374
He begins filming the week
 Britain declares war on Germany.

1:11:38.335 --> 1:11:41.171
In it, Chaplin collapses
          the distinctions

1:11:41.213 --> 1:11:42.548
between himself and Hitler

1:11:44.675 --> 1:11:47.678
as the dictator Adenoid Hynkel.

1:11:59.064 --> 1:12:01.066
But it's also a story
         of doppelgangers.

1:12:02.735 --> 1:12:06.280
He simultaneously plays
        the Jewish barber.

1:12:06.322 --> 1:12:08.782
Before we take you down,
     you'll finish this. Here!

1:12:11.076 --> 1:12:12.202
Come on. Paint that.

1:12:13.203 --> 1:12:14.330
Why you!

1:12:15.581 --> 1:12:17.166
- Ow!
         - Hey, come here!

1:12:17.207 --> 1:12:19.626
Chaplin, who wasn't Jewish,

1:12:19.668 --> 1:12:23.714
has finally aligned the
      Tramp with one identity.

1:12:26.925 --> 1:12:31.221
A persecuted minority
       facing extermination.

1:13:29.446 --> 1:13:31.031
At the film's end,

1:13:31.990 --> 1:13:34.785
the Tramp is mistaken
          for the dictator

1:13:39.373 --> 1:13:42.376
and forced to address the world.

1:13:47.089 --> 1:13:48.799
When the greatest
          comedy character

1:13:48.841 --> 1:13:51.093
of all time finally speaks,

1:13:53.095 --> 1:13:54.471
it's not to tell a joke.

1:13:57.474 --> 1:14:01.103
I'm sorry, but I don't
       want to be an emperor.

1:14:01.145 --> 1:14:02.438
That's not my business.

1:14:03.397 --> 1:14:05.899
I don't want to rule
         or conquer anyone.

1:14:05.941 --> 1:14:07.818
I should like to help
       everyone, if possible.

1:14:07.860 --> 1:14:11.321
Jew, Gentile, black men, white,

1:14:11.363 --> 1:14:12.906
we all want to help one another.

1:14:12.948 --> 1:14:14.908
Human beings are like that.

1:14:14.950 --> 1:14:16.285
We want to live
     by each other's happiness,

1:14:16.326 --> 1:14:18.162
not by each other's misery.

1:14:18.203 --> 1:14:20.664
We don't want to hate
      and despise one another.

1:14:20.706 --> 1:14:22.166
In this world
     there's room for everyone

1:14:22.207 --> 1:14:25.961
and the good earth is rich
   and can provide for everyone.

1:14:26.003 --> 1:14:29.089
The way of life can be
         free and beautiful,

1:14:29.131 --> 1:14:31.175
but we have lost the way.

1:14:31.216 --> 1:14:33.844
Greed has poisoned men's souls,

1:14:33.886 --> 1:14:36.180
has barricaded the
          world with hate,

1:14:36.221 --> 1:14:39.224
has goose-stepped us into
       misery and bloodshed.

1:14:39.266 --> 1:14:42.644
We have developed speed,
   but we have shut ourselves in.

1:14:42.686 --> 1:14:45.647
Machinery that gives
   abundance has left us in want.

1:14:45.689 --> 1:14:47.399
Our knowledge has
          made us cynical,

1:14:47.441 --> 1:14:49.735
our cleverness hard and unkind.

1:14:49.776 --> 1:14:52.196
We think too much
        and feel too little.

1:14:53.489 --> 1:14:55.032
You, the people have the power

1:14:55.073 --> 1:14:57.034
to make this life
        free and beautiful,

1:14:57.075 --> 1:14:59.495
to make this life
       a wonderful adventure.

1:14:59.536 --> 1:15:02.748
Then in the name of democracy,
       let us use that power.

1:15:02.789 --> 1:15:04.208
Let us all unite!

1:15:04.249 --> 1:15:07.920
Let us fight for a new
       world, a decent world,

1:15:07.961 --> 1:15:09.588
that will give men
         a chance to work,

1:15:09.630 --> 1:15:12.716
that will give you the future
      and old age a security.

1:15:12.758 --> 1:15:15.802
By the promise of these things,
    brutes have risen to power.

1:15:15.844 --> 1:15:18.555
But they lie. They do
     not fulfill that promise.

1:15:18.597 --> 1:15:20.057
They never will!

1:15:20.098 --> 1:15:23.560
Dictators free themselves,
    but they enslave the people.

1:15:23.602 --> 1:15:26.688
Now let us fight
      to fulfill that promise.

1:15:26.730 --> 1:15:29.149
Let us fight to free the world,

1:15:29.191 --> 1:15:31.235
to do away with
         national barriers,

1:15:31.276 --> 1:15:34.905
to do away with greed,
     with hate and intolerance.

1:15:34.947 --> 1:15:37.241
Let us fight for
         a world of reason,

1:15:37.282 --> 1:15:39.785
a world where science
       and progress will lead

1:15:39.826 --> 1:15:41.870
to all men's happiness.

1:15:41.912 --> 1:15:46.458
Soldiers, in the name of
    democracy, let us all unite!

1:16:00.764 --> 1:16:04.268
Chaplin knows
   the Tramp can't survive this.

1:16:07.980 --> 1:16:09.773
By breaking his silence,

1:16:11.525 --> 1:16:13.902
he's putting his
       creation on the alter.

1:16:19.199 --> 1:16:22.452
But after a quarter of a
   century in the Tramp costume,

1:16:25.747 --> 1:16:27.124
can Chaplin be sure

1:16:28.959 --> 1:16:30.794
that he will re-emerge whole?

1:16:35.173 --> 1:16:37.175
Can there be one

1:16:38.594 --> 1:16:40.053
without the other?

1:17:01.116 --> 1:17:02.784
It's 1947.

1:17:05.662 --> 1:17:07.831
Charlie Chaplin is
     holding a press conference

1:17:07.873 --> 1:17:09.625
at the Gotham Hotel in New York.

1:17:13.170 --> 1:17:15.505
He's about to release
      his new motion picture.

1:17:17.341 --> 1:17:19.885
His first without the Tramp.

1:17:22.554 --> 1:17:27.559
But as he knows, no one's
    here to talk about the film.

1:17:28.518 --> 1:17:29.978
Chaplin.

1:18:08.850 --> 1:18:11.937
So, how
          did we get here?

1:18:16.274 --> 1:18:19.277
"The Great Dictator" has
      been an enormous success

1:18:20.612 --> 1:18:23.448
and its closing speech
       has made such a splash

1:18:23.949 --> 1:18:26.410
that Chaplin is
        invited to repeat it

1:18:27.661 --> 1:18:31.998
at the inauguration of
 President Franklin D. Roosevelt.

1:18:32.040 --> 1:18:33.542
You, the
       people, have the power

1:18:33.583 --> 1:18:35.252
to make this life
        free and beautiful,

1:18:35.293 --> 1:18:37.963
to make this life a
        wonderful adventure

1:18:38.630 --> 1:18:42.676
that in the name of democracy,
       let us use that power.

1:18:42.718 --> 1:18:44.136
Let us all unite!

1:18:44.177 --> 1:18:46.888
At a fundraiser for
      the Russian war relief,

1:18:46.930 --> 1:18:49.558
he's invited to speak
         for four minutes.

1:18:49.599 --> 1:18:51.059
We must have a unity.

1:18:51.101 --> 1:18:52.310
He speaks for 40.

1:18:52.352 --> 1:18:55.147
And only by
       the strength of unity

1:18:55.188 --> 1:18:56.940
can we win this war.

1:18:56.982 --> 1:18:59.401
He gets carried
       away, goes off script.

1:18:59.443 --> 1:19:02.028
I certainly
     think if that's communism,

1:19:02.070 --> 1:19:03.613
there's a lot of people
       in the United States

1:19:03.655 --> 1:19:04.698
that'll vote for it.

1:19:07.784 --> 1:19:10.746
Having waited
   so long to break his silence,

1:19:12.164 --> 1:19:13.915
Chaplin can't stop talking.

1:19:14.958 --> 1:19:17.169
I just made
        a speech in Chicago

1:19:17.210 --> 1:19:20.672
and I happened to say that
 while people are anticommunist,

1:19:20.714 --> 1:19:22.883
I am going to be communistic.

1:19:24.593 --> 1:19:26.052
We must have the full strength

1:19:26.094 --> 1:19:28.472
from the capitalist
         to the communist,

1:19:28.513 --> 1:19:31.141
in order that we
       shall achieve victory.

1:19:34.936 --> 1:19:38.857
And people
      are starting to listen.

1:19:45.113 --> 1:19:47.491
Under the orders of its
        notorious director,

1:19:47.532 --> 1:19:49.785
J. Edgar Hoover,

1:19:49.826 --> 1:19:53.622
the FBI is engaged in
     wide ranging investigation

1:19:53.663 --> 1:19:55.665
into Chaplin's possible ties

1:19:56.833 --> 1:19:59.252
to the international
        communist movement.

1:20:02.464 --> 1:20:04.883
The Red Scare is underway,

1:20:06.051 --> 1:20:07.928
from Capitol hill to Hollywood.

1:20:09.721 --> 1:20:12.933
Communism in
     reality is akin to disease

1:20:12.974 --> 1:20:14.810
that's spread like an epidemic.

1:20:14.851 --> 1:20:16.436
And like an epidemic,

1:20:16.478 --> 1:20:20.023
a quarantine is necessary to
   keep from infecting the state.

1:20:21.107 --> 1:20:23.401
Actors, writers and filmmakers

1:20:23.443 --> 1:20:24.736
are dragged
       in front of the House

1:20:24.778 --> 1:20:27.113
un-American
       Activities Committee.

1:20:27.155 --> 1:20:28.615
Are you or
    have you ever been a member

1:20:28.657 --> 1:20:30.158
of the communist party?

1:20:30.200 --> 1:20:32.619
What is your
   opinion regarding communism?

1:20:32.661 --> 1:20:35.831
I feel that they really
      ought to be smoked out.

1:20:35.872 --> 1:20:36.832
If I had my way about it,

1:20:36.873 --> 1:20:38.792
they'd all be sent
           back to Russia

1:20:38.834 --> 1:20:41.086
or some other unpleasant place.

1:20:43.713 --> 1:20:47.050
10 Are imprisoned
      for refusing to testify.

1:20:51.096 --> 1:20:52.806
Hundreds are blacklisted.

1:20:54.766 --> 1:20:59.104
Taking down a big star would
     be a major coup for Hoover

1:21:00.897 --> 1:21:05.068
and they don't come much
    bigger than Charlie Chaplin.

1:21:05.110 --> 1:21:07.487
Are you a
   member of the communist party?

1:21:40.353 --> 1:21:43.315
But this response
      doesn't satisfy Hoover.

1:21:45.275 --> 1:21:47.193
Through the FBI's lens,

1:21:47.235 --> 1:21:49.613
Chaplin becomes not
         only a communist,

1:21:50.947 --> 1:21:52.574
but a foreign subversive,

1:21:53.783 --> 1:21:56.745
a homosexual, a Jew.

1:21:59.915 --> 1:22:02.417
It tells us a lot
         more about the FBI

1:22:02.459 --> 1:22:04.377
than it does about Chaplin.

1:22:08.423 --> 1:22:09.799
They're looking for dirt.

1:22:12.093 --> 1:22:16.514
And in this department,
     they have a powerful ally.

1:22:19.976 --> 1:22:21.311
Hello everybody.

1:22:21.353 --> 1:22:23.229
This is Hedda Hopper reporting
       to you from Hollywood.

1:22:23.271 --> 1:22:25.774
That fabulous place where
      everyone wants to live,

1:22:25.815 --> 1:22:27.442
but seldom does.

1:22:27.484 --> 1:22:30.028
"Hedda Hopper's
      Hollywood Gossip Column"

1:22:30.070 --> 1:22:33.156
is read by 32 million Americans.

1:22:33.198 --> 1:22:35.200
Work in Culver City and play.

1:22:35.241 --> 1:22:36.284
She has the power

1:22:36.326 --> 1:22:37.786
to make or break careers.

1:22:37.827 --> 1:22:40.038
Palm Springs, the other
     day I decided to get away-

1:22:40.080 --> 1:22:41.539
and she
         hates communists.

1:22:41.581 --> 1:22:43.792
Saw a little bit of sunshine.

1:22:43.833 --> 1:22:45.627
She tells Hoover,

1:22:45.669 --> 1:22:48.880
I'd like to run every one of
   those rats out of the country

1:22:50.632 --> 1:22:53.843
and start with Charlie Chaplin.

1:22:58.306 --> 1:23:02.018
The file shows that Hopper
      and Hoover's relationship

1:23:02.060 --> 1:23:03.895
is more or less circular.

1:23:06.064 --> 1:23:08.900
Hopper fills her columns
     with gossip about Chaplin

1:23:10.193 --> 1:23:12.612
that's been fed
         to her by the FBI.

1:23:12.654 --> 1:23:14.155
Charlie Chaplin dividing

1:23:14.197 --> 1:23:15.657
his dancing attention night
 before last at the Persian Room-

1:23:15.699 --> 1:23:18.034
The FBI
     then quotes those columns

1:23:18.868 --> 1:23:20.370
and its file against Chaplin.

1:23:20.412 --> 1:23:21.705
In the minds of...

1:23:21.746 --> 1:23:24.708
Charlie Chaplin is called
     the debutante's delight.

1:23:24.749 --> 1:23:27.043
The
       machine feeds itself.

1:23:27.085 --> 1:23:30.130
Regarding
      communists in Hollywood.

1:23:30.171 --> 1:23:32.048
I found much .

1:23:32.090 --> 1:23:35.719
The evidence,
 however, remains circumstantial.

1:23:38.930 --> 1:23:40.015
Until one day-

1:23:40.056 --> 1:23:41.516
You know, there's one
         man in particular-

1:23:41.558 --> 1:23:46.646
Hopper finds a
   young woman called Joan Barry.

1:23:53.361 --> 1:23:56.948
In 1941, Joan
        arrived in Hollywood

1:23:56.990 --> 1:23:59.242
as an aspiring young actress.

1:24:04.914 --> 1:24:07.083
Charlie Chaplin
      took an interest in her.

1:24:09.210 --> 1:24:11.129
He said he could
          make her a star.

1:24:16.092 --> 1:24:20.263
Now she's pregnant
        and she needs help.

1:24:25.143 --> 1:24:28.938
Hopper and Hoover
       sense an opportunity.

1:24:33.568 --> 1:24:36.863
Chaplin is taken to court to
    prove that he's the father.

1:24:39.491 --> 1:24:42.577
And Hopper ensures the
        whole case plays out,

1:24:42.619 --> 1:24:46.831
week-by-week in
         the tabloid press.

1:24:50.502 --> 1:24:52.962
The prosecutor
        tears into Chaplin.

1:24:55.131 --> 1:24:57.342
He reveals that
        Chaplin forced Barry

1:24:57.383 --> 1:24:59.469
to have two backstreet abortions

1:25:00.887 --> 1:25:04.307
and accuses him of decades
       of predatory behavior.

1:25:08.978 --> 1:25:11.189
Three grueling trials later,

1:25:13.608 --> 1:25:16.319
a blood test suggests he
       may not be the father.

